can male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American naval officers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Pembroke College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:American LGBT military personnel]]\n[[Category:American Rhodes Scholars]]\n[[Category:American memoirists]]\n[[Category:American naval personnel of the War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)]]\n[[Category:American people of Maltese descent]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2010 United States elections]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2020 United States presidential election]]\n[[Category:Converts to Anglicanism from Roman Catholicism]]\n[[Category:Former Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Gay military personnel]]\n[[Category:Gay politicians]]\n[[Category:Gay writers]]\n[[Category:Harvard College alumni]]\n[[Category:Indiana Democrats]]\n[[Category:LGBT Anglicans]]\n[[Category:LGBT mayors of places in the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT memoirists]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Indiana]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mayors of South Bend, Indiana]]\n[[Category:McKinsey & Company people]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Indiana]]\n[[Category:Progressivism in the United States]]\n[[Category:United States Navy reservists]]\n[[Category:Writers from South Bend, Indiana]]\n", "name_user": "KRed221", "label": "safe", "comment": "I stated facts", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pete_Buttigieg"}
{"title_page": "Homelite Corporation", "text_new": "{{advert|date=October 2018}}\n{{More references|date=January 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox company|\n name = Homelite Corporation|\n type = Public |\n logo = Homelite logo.svg |\n logo_caption     = |\n foundation =  |\n location = |\n caption =  |\n key_people = |\n homepage = {{URL|https://www.homelite.com/}} |\nnum_employees =  |\n revenue = |\n industry = |\n products =  \n}}\n\n[[File:Homelite Super XL Automatic Chainsaw.jpg|200px|thumb|Homelite Super XL Automatic Chainsaw: Upgraded version of XL-12 (has automatic bar/chain oiler).]]\n'''Homelite Corporation''' is an American power equipment manufacturer, i.e. ([[chainsaw]]s, [[leaf blower]]s, [[Trimmer (gardening)|trimmers]]), that became notable as being  one of the largest post-[[World War II]] manufacturers of portable [[electrical generator]]s and  professional and consumer level chainsaws, as well as holding the distinction of producing the world's first one-man operated chainsaw.\n\n== History ==\n\n'''Beginnings'''\n\nIn 1921, entrepreneur Charles H. Ferguson of [[Port Chester, New York]], invented a lightweight, portable, [[gasoline]]-powered electrical generator. His newly founded company, the Home Electric Lighting Company (later abbreviated to Homelite), made it possible for thousands of rural farms and households to enjoy the convenience of electricity, where it would be years before land lines would reach many of these remote areas. In addition, many of Mr. Ferguson's generators played a significant role in the [[war effort]], providing portable electricity on demand for the troops during World War II.\n\n'''Chainsaws'''\n\n[[Image:Homelite1.jpg|200px|thumb|left|Homelite 330 chainsaw flanked by two Homelite Super XL Automatic Chainsaws.]]\n\nIn 1946, Homelite manufactured its first chainsaw, an electrical model, and in 1949, released another power-equipment innovation in the form of the first chainsaw that featured '''one-man operation''' (previous saws were generally too large and bulky to be operated by a single individual). By the mid-1960s, Homelite had been firmly established as one of the largest manufacturers of chainsaws in the world, with models ranging from small brush cutters, to the most advanced professional [[logging]] saws. The year 1963 saw the introduction of the world's first \"lightweight\" chainsaw, the magnesium-alloy framed Homelite XL-12; the numeral twelve denoting that the power-head weighed a mere twelve pounds. This saw is widely regarded as one of the most recognizable and well-known chainsaws of all time. In addition, the XL-12 achieved notoriety among [[horror film]] aficionados, being used in films like [[The Evil Dead]] and its sequels.\n\nBeginning in the late 1970s, Homelite gradually expanded its power equipment line to include [[string trimmer]]s, leaf blowers, and [[hedge trimmer]]s. John Deere acquired the brand in the 1980s.\n\n[[Techtronic Industries]] acquired Homelite from John Deere in 2001.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lawnandlandscape.com/article/john-deere---company-sells-homelite-brand/|title=John Deere & Company Sells Homelite Brand|last=|first=|date=2001-11-21|website=Lawn & Landscape|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> Homelite has shifted its production primarily to consumer level lawn and garden equipment and light duty chainsaws. Replacement parts for the older, professional-grade, saws are generally limited to [[new old stock]] (NOS) and salvage parts. However, these saws were built to last, and a good percentage of them are still in use to this day. Homelite's [[Holding company|parent company]] is headquartered in Hong Kong.[[Image:TexasChainsawMassacreTNG.jpg|200px|thumb|Homelite XL-12 Chainsaw featured on poster for ''Texas Chainsaw Massacre - The Next Generation'' film.]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.homelite.com/}}\n{{Techtronic Industries}}\n{{Power tool manufacturers}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Agricultural machinery manufacturers of the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{advert|date=October 2018}}\n{{unreferenced|date=January 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox company|\n name = Homelite Corporation|\n type = Public |\n logo = Homelite logo.svg |\n logo_caption     = |\n foundation =  |\n location = |\n caption =  |\n key_people = |\n homepage = {{URL|https://www.homelite.com/}} |\nnum_employees =  |\n revenue = |\n industry = |\n products =  \n}}\n\n[[File:Homelite Super XL Automatic Chainsaw.jpg|200px|thumb|Homelite Super XL Automatic Chainsaw: Upgraded version of XL-12 (has automatic bar/chain oiler).]]\n'''Homelite Corporation''' is an American power equipment manufacturer, i.e. ([[chainsaw]]s, [[leaf blower]]s, [[Trimmer (gardening)|trimmers]]), that became notable as being  one of the largest post-[[World War II]] manufacturers of portable [[electrical generator]]s and  professional and consumer level chainsaws, as well as holding the distinction of producing the world's first one-man operated chainsaw.\n\n== History ==\n\n'''Beginnings'''\n\nIn 1921, entrepreneur Charles H. Ferguson of [[Port Chester, New York]], invented a lightweight, portable, [[gasoline]]-powered electrical generator. His newly founded company, the Home Electric Lighting Company (later abbreviated to Homelite), made it possible for thousands of rural farms and households to enjoy the convenience of electricity, where it would be years before land lines would reach many of these remote areas. In addition, many of Mr. Ferguson's generators played a significant role in the [[war effort]], providing portable electricity on demand for the troops during World War II.\n\n'''Chainsaws'''\n\n[[Image:Homelite1.jpg|200px|thumb|left|Homelite 330 chainsaw flanked by two Homelite Super XL Automatic Chainsaws.]]\n\nIn 1946, Homelite manufactured its first chainsaw, an electrical model, and in 1949, released another power-equipment innovation in the form of the first chainsaw that featured '''one-man operation''' (previous saws were generally too large and bulky to be operated by a single individual). By the mid-1960s, Homelite had been firmly established as one of the largest manufacturers of chainsaws in the world, with models ranging from small brush cutters, to the most advanced professional [[logging]] saws. The year 1963 saw the introduction of the world's first \"lightweight\" chainsaw, the magnesium-alloy framed Homelite XL-12; the numeral twelve denoting that the power-head weighed a mere twelve pounds. This saw is widely regarded as one of the most recognizable and well-known chainsaws of all time. In addition, the XL-12 achieved notoriety among [[horror film]] aficionados, being used in films like [[The Evil Dead]] and its sequels.\n\nBeginning in the late 1970s, Homelite gradually expanded its power equipment line to include [[string trimmer]]s, leaf blowers, and [[hedge trimmer]]s. John Deere acquired the brand in the 1980s.\n\n[[Techtronic Industries]] acquired Homelite from John Deere in 2001<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lawnandlandscape.com/article/john-deere---company-sells-homelite-brand/|title=John Deere & Company Sells Homelite Brand|last=|first=|date=2001-11-21|website=Lawn & Landscape|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>. Homelite has shifted its production primarily to consumer level lawn and garden equipment and light duty chainsaws. Replacement parts for the older, professional-grade, saws are generally limited to [[new old stock]] (NOS) and salvage parts. However, these saws were built to last, and a good percentage of them are still in use to this day. Homelite's [[Holding company|parent company]] is headquartered in Hong Kong.[[Image:TexasChainsawMassacreTNG.jpg|200px|thumb|Homelite XL-12 Chainsaw featured on poster for ''Texas Chainsaw Massacre - The Next Generation'' film.]]\n<br />\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.homelite.com/}}\n{{Techtronic Industries}}\n{{Power tool manufacturers}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Agricultural machinery manufacturers of the United States]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reflist", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Homelite_Corporation"}
{"title_page": "Deborah Acquah", "text_new": "{{short description|Ghanaian long jumper}}\n'''Deborah Acquah''' (born May 23, 1996) is a Ghanaian Long jumper. She has competed at world championships, most recently at the [[2019 African Games]] in [[Rabat]], [[Morocco]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.graphic.com.gh/sports/sports-news/ghana-news-acquah-wins-silver-in-long-jump.html|title=Acquah wins Silver in long jump|website=Graphic Online|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://worldathletics.org/athletes/ghana/deborah-acquah-333886|title=Deborah ACQUAH {{!}} Profile|website=worldathletics.org|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.myjoyonline.com/sports/2019/August-30th/african-games-deborah-acquah-wins-silver-medal-in-womens-long-jump.php|title=African Games: Deborah Acquah wins silver medal in Women\u2019s Long Jump|website=www.myjoyonline.com|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref> She is the current holder of Ghana's indoor long and triple jump records.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://kuulpeeps.com/2020/02/deborah-acquah-sets-new-triple-jump-record-at-charlie-thomas-invitational/|title=Deborah Acquah Sets New Triple Jump Record At Charlie Thomas Invitational - Kuulpeeps - Ghana Campus News and Lifestyle Site by Students|last=Sedode|first=Pilot|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nAcquah had her secondary school education at  Fiaseman Senior High School. She was a student of Western Texas College but is now currently having her college education at Texas A&M University.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/SportsArchive/NCAA-Deborah-Acquah-wins-bronze-in-long-jump-Bissah-Amoah-miss-out-on-medals-753127|title=NCAA: Deborah Acquah wins bronze in long jump; Bissah, Amoah miss out on medals|website=www.ghanaweb.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nIn August 2019, she competed at the 2019 African Games in Rabat and won a silver medal for Ghana with a jump of 6.37 m in the Women's Long Jump.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghanabusinessnews.com/2019/08/30/deborah-acquah-wins-silver-medal-in-womens-long-jump/|title=Deborah Acquah wins silver medal in Women\u2019s Long Jump|last=myadmin|date=2019-08-30|website=Ghana Business News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ghanasportsonline.com/2019/08/african-games-2019-deborah-acquah-grabs-silver-for-ghana-in-womens-long-jump/|title=AFRICAN GAMES 2019: Deborah Acquah grabs silver for Ghana in Women\u2019s Long Jump|date=2019-08-29|website=Ghana Sports Online|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> She also competed in the NCAA Division 1 Championships in Austin, Texas and won a bronze  in the women's long jump.<ref name=\":1\" />In January 2020, her 21 foot six inch long jump broke a 22 year school record by four inches at the Ted Nelson Invitational.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theeagle.com/sports/new-focus-helps-acquah-break-texas-a-m-womens-long-jump-record/article_6a557482-3d98-11ea-b10d-439401918839.html|title=New focus helps Acquah break Texas A&M women's long jump record|last=travis.brown@theeagle.com|first=TRAVIS L. BROWN|website=The Eagle|language=en|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> In February 2020, she broke the Texas A&M triple jump record to win first place at the Charlie Thomas Invitational.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kagstv.com/article/sports/aggiestrack/499-65b1cabb-f898-4c0f-9843-35c95ce32d06|title=Deborah Acquah breaks school record in Charlie Thomas Invitational|website=KAGS|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n\n== Personal bests ==\n\n* Long jump: 6.63 m, NCAA Championships in Texas<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://12thman.com/sports/mens-track-and-field/roster/deborah-acquah/7678|title=Deborah Acquah - Track and Field|website=Texas A&M Athletics - Home of the 12th Man|language=en|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" />\n*Triple jump:13.77m, Charlie Thomas Invitational meet in College Station, Texas.<ref name=\":2\" />\n*Long jump:6.57m ,Ted Nelson Invitational in Texas.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Acquah, Deborah}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian sportswomen]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian long jumpers]]\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:African sportspeople]]\n[[Category:African Games silver medalists for Ghana]]\n[[Category:African Games medalists in athletics (track and field)]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2019 African Games]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Ghanaian long jumper}}\n'''Deborah Acquah''' (born May 23, 1996) is a Ghanaian Long jumper. She has competed at world championships, most recently at the [[2019 African Games]] in [[Rabat]], [[Morocco]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.graphic.com.gh/sports/sports-news/ghana-news-acquah-wins-silver-in-long-jump.html|title=Acquah wins Silver in long jump|website=Graphic Online|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://worldathletics.org/athletes/ghana/deborah-acquah-333886|title=Deborah ACQUAH {{!}} Profile|website=worldathletics.org|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.myjoyonline.com/sports/2019/August-30th/african-games-deborah-acquah-wins-silver-medal-in-womens-long-jump.php|title=African Games: Deborah Acquah wins silver medal in Women\u2019s Long Jump|website=www.myjoyonline.com|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref> She is the current holder of Ghana's indoor long and triple jump records.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://kuulpeeps.com/2020/02/deborah-acquah-sets-new-triple-jump-record-at-charlie-thomas-invitational/|title=Deborah Acquah Sets New Triple Jump Record At Charlie Thomas Invitational - Kuulpeeps - Ghana Campus News and Lifestyle Site by Students|last=Sedode|first=Pilot|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nAcquah had he