{"title_page": "Deuce (video album)", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Deuce\n| type       = video\n| artist     = [[Korn]]\n| cover      = Deuce (Korn DVD).jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = June 11, 2002<ref>https://www.allmusic.com/album/mw0001245374</ref>\n| recorded   = 1993-2001\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Nu metal]], [[alternative metal]]\n| length     = 150 min.<ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0339267/</ref>\n| label      = [[Sony]], [[Epic Records|Epic]]\n| director   = [[Nathan Cox]]\n| producer   = Nathan Cox\n| prev_title = [[Who Then Now?]]\n| prev_year  = 1997\n| next_title = [[Live (Korn DVD)|Live]]\n| next_year  = 2002\n}}\n'''''Deuce''''' is the second video album by American [[nu metal]] band [[Korn]]. The [[DVD]] was released on 11 June 2002, on the same day as the band's fifth studio album, ''[[Untouchables (album)|Untouchables]]''. It was certified [[platinum record|platinum]] by the [[RIAA]] in July 2002.<ref>https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&ar=KORN&ti=DEUCE</ref> ''Deuce'' includes the band's biographical video, ''[[Who Then Now?]]'', as well as music videos from albums [[Korn (album)|''Korn'']] up to [[Issues (Korn album)|''Issues'']]. Other extras include biographies of each band member, gags, behind-the-scenes and live concerts.\n\n==Track listing==\n*\"[[Blind (Korn song)|Blind]]\"\n*\"[[Clown (Korn song)|Clown]]\"\n*\"[[Shoots and Ladders (song)|Shoots and Ladders]]\"\n*\"[[Faget (song)|Faget]]\"\n*\"[[A.D.I.D.A.S. (Korn song)|A.D.I.D.A.S.]]\"\n*\"[[Got the Life]]\"\n*\"[[Freak on a Leash]]\"\n*\"[[Falling Away from Me]]\"\n*\"[[Make Me Bad]]\"\n*\"[[Somebody Someone]]\"\n\n==See also==\n{{Wikipedia-Books|Korn}}\n*[[Korn discography#Video albums|Korn video albums]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*{{Allmusic | class= album| id=mw0001245374| label= Deuce | accessdate= 16:52, 21 August 2016 (UTC) }}\n\n{{Korn}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Deuce (Korn Dvd)}}\n[[Category:Korn video albums]]\n[[Category:2002 compilation albums]]\n[[Category:Music video compilation albums]]\n[[Category:2002 video albums]]\n\n\n{{2000s-metal-album-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{2000s-metal-album-stub}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Deuce\n| type       = video\n| artist     = [[Korn]]\n| cover      = Deuce (Korn DVD).jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = June 11, 2002<ref>https://www.allmusic.com/album/mw0001245374</ref>\n| recorded   = 1993-2001\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Nu metal]], [[alternative metal]]\n| length     = 150 min.<ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0339267/</ref>\n| label      = [[Sony]], [[Epic Records|Epic]]\n| director   = [[Nathan Cox]]\n| producer   = Nathan Cox\n| prev_title = [[Who Then Now?]]\n| prev_year  = 1997\n| next_title = [[Live (Korn DVD)|Live]]\n| next_year  = 2002\n}}\n'''''Deuce''''' is the second video album by American [[nu metal]] band [[Korn]]. The [[DVD]] was released on 11 June 2002, on the same day as the band's fifth studio album, ''[[Untouchables (album)|Untouchables]]''. It was certified [[platinum record|platinum]] by the [[RIAA]] in July 2002<ref>https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&ar=KORN&ti=DEUCE</ref>. ''Deuce'' includes the band's biographical video, ''[[Who Then Now?]]'', as well as music videos from albums [[Korn (album)|''Korn'']] up to [[Issues (Korn album)|''Issues'']]. Other extras include biographies of each band member, gags, behind-the-scenes and live concerts.\n\n==Track listing==\n*\"[[Blind (Korn song)|Blind]]\"\n*\"[[Clown (Korn song)|Clown]]\"\n*\"[[Shoots and Ladders (song)|Shoots and Ladders]]\"\n*\"[[Faget (song)|Faget]]\"\n*\"[[A.D.I.D.A.S. (Korn song)|A.D.I.D.A.S.]]\"\n*\"[[Got the Life]]\"\n*\"[[Freak on a Leash]]\"\n*\"[[Falling Away from Me]]\"\n*\"[[Make Me Bad]]\"\n*\"[[Somebody Someone]]\"\n\n==See also==\n{{Wikipedia-Books|Korn}}\n*[[Korn discography#Video albums|Korn video albums]]\n\n==References==                 \n*{{Allmusic | class= album| id=mw0001245374| label= Deuce | accessdate= 16:52, 21 August 2016 (UTC) }}\n\n{{Korn}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Deuce (Korn Dvd)}}\n[[Category:Korn video albums]]\n[[Category:2002 compilation albums]]\n[[Category:Music video compilation albums]]\n[[Category:2002 video albums]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reflist", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deuce_(video_album)"}
{"title_page": "Refrigerated container", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=December 2009}}\n[[Image:Volvo FH12-Inger (F)-2003.jpg|thumb|Reefer on a truck]]\n[[Image:Stack of containers.JPG|thumb|left|upright|Containers loaded on a [[container ship]] with the refrigeration units visible]]\n[[File:Interior Reefercontainer.JPG|thumb|Inside of a refrigerated container]]\n[[File:Reefer_container_stacked.jpeg|thumbnail|right|Reefer containers]]\n[[File:Reefer Socket.jpg|thumb|Reefer sockets used to power reefer containers]]\nA '''refrigerated container''' or '''reefer''' is an [[intermodal container]] (shipping container) used in [[intermodal freight transport]] that is [[Refrigeration|refrigerated]] for the transportation of temperature-sensitive cargo.\n\nWhile a reefer will have an integral refrigeration unit, they rely on external power, from electrical power points (\u201creefer points\u201d) at a land-based site, a [[container ship]] or on [[quay]]. When being transported over the road on a trailer or over rail wagon, they can be powered from [[Diesel engine|diesel powered]] [[Electrical generator|generators]] (\"gen sets\") which attach to the container whilst on road journeys. Refrigerated containers are capable of controlling temperature ranging from -65 \u00b0C up to 40 \u00b0C.<ref name=\"File\">{{cite web\n |title      = Refrigerated container\n |work       = wifi tech\n |url        = https://www.wifitech.online/2020/04/reefer-container.html\n |date       = April 2020\n |accessdate = 2020-04-18\n}}</ref>\nSome reefers are equipped with a water cooling system, which can be used if the reefer is stored below deck on a vessel without adequate ventilation to remove the heat generated.<ref>{{cite web| title=Reefer container meaning and definition|url=https://www.alconet-containers.com/reefer-container-meaning-and-definition/| website=Alconet Containers|accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nWater cooling systems are more expensive than air current ventilation to remove heat from cargo holds, and the use of water cooling systems is declining.<ref name=\"File\"/> Air cooling and water cooling are usually combined. Air cooling removes the heat generated by the reefers while water cooling helps to minimise the heat produced by the reefers. The reefers are using some heat exchangers that behaves as water cooled condensers: water cooling.\n\nThe impact on society of reefer containers is vast, allowing consumers all over the world to enjoy fresh [[produce]] at any time of year and experience previously unavailable [[Post harvest freshness|fresh]] produce from many other parts of the world.\n\n==Cryogenic cooling==\nAnother refrigeration system sometimes used where the journey time is short is [[Refrigeration#Non-cyclic refrigeration|total loss refrigeration]], in which [[dry ice|frozen carbon dioxide ice]] (or sometimes [[liquid nitrogen]]) is used for cooling.<ref name=\"IIR2003\"/>  The cryogenically frozen gas slowly evaporates, and thus cools the container and is vented from it. The container is cooled for as long as there is frozen gas available in the system. These have been used in railcars for many years, providing up to 17 days temperature regulation.<ref name=\"cryopower\"/> Whilst refrigerated containers are not common for air transport, total loss dry ice systems are usually used.<ref name=\"IIR2003\">{{cite web|\ntitle = Refrigerated transport: Progress achieved and challenges to be met|\nwork = International Institute of Refrigeration|\nurl= http://www.iifiir.org/en/doc/1014.pdf|\ndate = August 2003|\naccessdate=2010-05-01\n}}</ref> These containers have a chamber which is loaded with solid carbon dioxide and the temperature is regulated by a thermostatically controlled electric fan, and the air freight versions are intended to maintain temperature for up to around 100 hours.<ref name=\"envirotainer\">{{cite book\n |title       = Refrigerated container with temperature control RKN series and RAP series Operation manual\n |publisher   = Envirotainer Engineering\n |url         = http://www.jalcargobkk.com/info/envirotainer_operation_manual.pdf\n |date        = August 2001\n |accessdate  = 2010-05-01\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20171008232330/http://www.jalcargobkk.com/info/envirotainer_operation_manual.pdf\n |archivedate = 2017-10-08\n}}</ref>\n\nFull-size intermodal containers equipped with these \"cryogenic\" systems can maintain their temperature for the 30 days needed for sea transport.<ref name=\"cryopower\">{{cite web|title=History |work=Cryo-Power Enterprises LLC |url=http://www.containerserviceco.com/history.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090627104857/http://www.containerserviceco.com/history.html |archivedate=June 27, 2009 }}</ref> Since they do not require an external power supply, cryogenically refrigerated containers can be stored anywhere on any vessel that can accommodate \"dry\" (un-refrigerated) ocean freight containers.\n\n==Redundant refrigeration==\n[[File:Redundantreefer.JPG|thumb|A container fitted with two refrigeration units and a single diesel generator]]\nValuable, temperature-sensitive, or hazardous cargo often require the utmost in system reliability.  This type of reliability can only be achieved through the installation of a '''redundant refrigeration system'''.\n\nA redundant refrigeration system consists of integrated primary and back-up refrigeration units. If the primary unit malfunctions, the secondary unit automatically starts. To provide reliable power to the refrigeration units, these containers are often fitted with one or more [[diesel generator]] sets.\n\nContainers fitted with these systems may be required for transporting certain [[dangerous goods]] in order to comply with the [[International Maritime Organization]]\u2019s regulations.\n\n==Reefer types and dimensions==\nThe reefer cannot be loaded in double-stack on rail flatcar.\n\n==See also==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Cold chain]]\n* [[Insulated shipping container]]\n* [[Reefer ship]]\n* [[Refrigerator car]]\n* [[Refrigerator truck]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{Intermodal containers}}\n{{Commonscat|Refrigerated containers}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Refrigerated Container}}\n[[Category:Freight rolling stock]]\n[[Category:Cooling technology]]\n[[Category:Intermodal containers]]\n[[Category:Port infrastructure]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=December 2009}}\n[[Image:Volvo FH12-Inger (F)-2003.jpg|thumb|Reefer on a truck]]\n[[Image:Stack of containers.JPG|thumb|left|upright|Containers loaded on a [[container ship]] with the refrigeration units visible]]\n[[File:Interior Reefercontainer.JPG|thumb|Inside of a refrigerated container]]\n[[File:Reefer_container_stacked.jpeg|thumbnail|right|Reefer containers]]\n[[File:Reefer Socket.jpg|thumb|Reefer sockets used to power reefer containers]]\nA '''refrigerated container''' or '''reefer''' is an [[intermodal container]] (shipping container) used in [[intermodal freight transport]] that is [[Refrigeration|refrigerated]] for the transportation of temperature-sensitive cargo.\n\nWhile a reefer will have an integral refrigeration unit, they rely on external power, from electrical power points (\u201creefer points\u201d) at a land-based site, a [[container ship]] or on [[quay]]. When being transported over the road on a trailer or over rail wagon, they can be powered from [[Diesel engine|diesel powered]] [[Electrical generator|generators]] (\"gen sets\") which attach to the container whilst on road journeys. Refrigerated containers are capable of controlling temperature ranging from -65 \u00b0C up to 40 \u00b0C.<ref name=\"File\">{{cite web\n |title      = Bewaking temperatuur tijdens transport van levensmiddelen over grote afstanden. (NL)\n |work       = Innotact Consulting B.V.\n |url        = https://www.nvwa.nl/txmpub/files/?p_file_id=38505\n |date       = October 2008\n |accessdate = 2015-06-30\n}}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nSome reefers are equipped with a water cooling system, which can be used if the reefer is stored below deck on a vessel without adequate ventilation to remove the heat generated.<ref>{{cite web| title=Reefer container meaning and definition|url=https://www.alconet-containers.com/reefer-container-meaning-and-definition/| website=Alconet Containers|accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nWater cooling systems are more expensive than air current ventilation to remove heat from cargo holds, and the use of water cooling systems is declining.<ref name=\"File\"/> Air cooling and water cooling are usually combined. Air cooling removes the heat generated by the reefers while water cooling helps to minimise the heat produced by the reefers. The reefers are using some heat exchangers that behaves as water cooled condensers: water cooling.\n\nThe impact on society of reefer containers is vast, allowing consumers all over the world to enjoy fresh [[produce]] at any time of year and experience previously unavailable [[Post harvest freshness|fresh]] produce from many other parts of the world.\n\n==Cryogenic cooling==\nAnother refrigeration system sometimes used where the journey time is short is [[Refrigeration#Non-cyclic refrigeration|total loss refrigeration]], in which [[dry ice|frozen carbon dioxide ice]] (or sometimes [[liquid nitrogen]]) is used for cooling.<ref name=\"IIR2003\"/>  The cryogenically frozen gas slowly evaporates, and thus cools the container and is vented from it. The container is cooled for as long as there is frozen gas available in the system. These have been used in railcars for many years, providing up to 17 days temperature regulation.<ref name=\"cryopower\"/> Whilst refrigerated containers are not common for air transport, total loss dry ice systems are usually used.<ref name=\"IIR2003\">{{cite web|\ntitle = Refrigerated transport: Progress achieved and challenges to be met|\nwork = International Institute of Refrigeration|\nurl= http://www.iifiir.org/en/doc/1014.pdf|\ndate = August 2003|\naccessdate=2010-05-01\n}}</ref> These containers have a chamber which is loaded with solid carbon dioxide and the temperature is regulated by a thermostatically controlled electric fan, and the air freight versions are intended to maintain temperature for up to around 100 hours.<ref name=\"envirotainer\">{{cite book\n |title       = Refrigerated container with temperature control RKN series and RAP series Operation manual\n |publisher   = Envirotainer Engineering\n |url         = http://www.jalcargobkk.com/info/envirotainer_operation_manual.pdf\n |date        = August 2001\n |accessdate  = 2010-05-01\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20171008232330/http://www.jalcargobkk.com/info/envirotainer_operation_manual.pdf\n |archivedate = 2017-10-08\n}}</ref>\n\nFull-size intermodal containers equipped with these \"cryogenic\" systems can maintain their temperature for the 30 days needed for sea transport.<ref name=\"cryopower\">{{cite web|title=History |work=Cryo-Power Enterprises LLC |url=http://www.containerserviceco.com/history.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090627104857/http://www.containerserviceco.com/history.html |archivedate=June 27, 2009 }}</ref> Since they do not require an external power supply, cryogenically refrigerated containers can be stored anywhere on any vessel that can accommodate \"dry\" (un-refrigerated) ocean freight containers.\n\n==Redundant refrigeration==\n[[File:Redundantreefer.JPG|thumb|A container fitted with two refrigeration units and a single diesel generator]]\nValuable, temperature-sensitive, or hazardous cargo often require the utmost in system reliability.  This type of reliability can only be achieved through the installation of a '''redundant refrigeration system'''.\n\nA redundant refrigeration system consists of integrated primary and back-up refrigeration units. If the primary unit malfunctions, the secondary unit automatically starts. To provide reliable power to the refrigeration units, these containers are often fitted with one or more [[diesel generator]] sets.\n\nContainers fitted with these systems may be required for transporting certain [[dangerous goods]] in order to comply with the [[International Maritime Organization]]\u2019s regulations.\n\n==Reefer types and dimensions==\nThe reefer cannot be loaded in double-stack on rail flatcar.\n\n==See also==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Cold chain]]\n* [[Insulated shipping container]]\n* [[Reefer ship]]\n* [[Refrigerator car]]\n* [[Refrigerator truck]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{Intermodal containers}}\n{{Commonscat|Refrigerated containers}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Refrigerated Container}}\n[[Category:Freight rolling stock]]\n[[Category:Cooling technology]]\n[[Category:Intermodal containers]]\n[[Category:Port infrastructure]]\n", "name_user": "Bhushan.surve", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Dead link deleted and provided reference page link.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Refrigerated_container"}
